MY DOCUMENTATION SYSTEM

A wiki documentation system made using GNU Make and Pandoc that integrates with the operating system for quick note-taking

Overview

I always had trouble with organizing files in my computer, especially when it comes to text files and notes, so I decided to try a few organization systems and applications like Emacs Org Mode, Vim Wiki and others, but I didn‚Äôt quite adapt to these systems, as they offered too many functions that I don‚Äôt need, so I decided to create my own simple wiki using nothing but a makefile and Pandoc (and also a custom binary I wrote in C++ used to generate the main wiki file.)

How it works

The wiki is composed of sections, which contain pages, each section is a directory inside the pages directory and each page is a markdown file in any section directory.

A makefile uses a parser to to build the html (or pdf) output. The parser manipulates the filenames to create the main wiki page.

  • pages
    • to_do
      • supermarket_stuf.md
      • project_ideas.md
    • my_creepy_stories
      • the_old_house.md
      • the_killer_pencil_from_outer_space.md

The parser

To avoid a series of sed operations, I decided to do the parsing and text manipulation in a separate script, but since this little system had the purpose of testing interesting things, I decided to create a C++ program to test the std::filesystem, from C++17. (Python would be more appropriate).

The parser receives the filenames and outputs the edited text to standard output in the form of a markdown link [Filename](path/to/filename)

The makefile

The makefile presents two options: html and pdf, the latter is preferred, since not all pdf readers support opening other files.

Operating System Integration

There‚Äôs a .wiki_alias file, which is a bash script that creates some aliases and is run in the .bashrc file. This way it‚Äôs possible to quickly access and edit a task, page, project idea, etc.

The output

The output is a new directory wiki, which contains the html (and pdf) with all of the working links.
